This was a really nice restaurant that we had always been wanting to try. The service there was excellent. I ordered the pumpkin soup and saw what looked like was an eyelash in my soup but could have possibly been pumpkin pulp so I asked the waitress to send it back. One waiter said it was not a hair but our waitress said she didn't want to take any chances and sent it back for a new one. The soup itself was delicious. The only reason why I gave it four stars instead of 5 is because when I got my burger, it had coleslaw on top and I could tell that the coleslaw was not fresh it was a bit wilted and kind of brown looking. I was just expecting something very fresh and crunchy but it wasn't. That's not to say it still wasn't delicious because it was I just would have liked for a fresh coleslaw. Another thing too is... I'm not sure if the bathrooms were under construction but there was only one public restroom for the restaurant and it was literally a single toilet and sink so there was a line to use the restroom too.

Christmas Day and not many places open for breakfast but Atwood is. So three of us came for the Late Breakfast (10:30-11:30) and were told all the tables were booked for lunch even though we'd be in an out pretty fast. Fine. Fine. I went outside and called the place not five minutes later. The SAME GUY told me on the phone they had two 4 tops free until 1:30 so I could "come any time".  We're all guys, professionals and dressed pretty nicely, and it's our first time visiting Chicago. What a horrible impression.  (Edit: ended up at another spot opposite Trump hotel where we were staying and staff was very kind and welcoming.)

Highly suggest making reservations! Such a great lunch. Many of the cocktails looked good but we got got the lion’s tail. The spinach artichoke dip was really good! Seemed like the spinach was chopped/blended well so that it looked almost like a pesto dip! Very good! The Brussels sprouts has a great sauce that it was served in. They were not crunchy/fried, but more like steamed and baked. (I’m guessing)  The burger and the fried chicken sandwich are both great choices for your main.  Definitely will return for another meal sometime!

Most importantly, the staff was knowledgeable but friendly, lacking the haughtiness sometimes found in big city downtown restaurants and hotels.

Excellent service, friendly and attentive. Anticipating our needs. Atmosphere, modern  clean, bright, inviting. Food delicious, good presentation, portion size appropriate. Issue was with the wait staff uniforms, tee shirts, which were more appropriate for a fast food restaurant.  The pineapple logo design on the plates was elegant, tasteful and matched the environment. The uniform would be more appropriate if it were white shirt, small black vest, yellow tie with just the pineapple logo. Everyone may be happier as it would compliment the decor.
Great place for a bite to eat (salmon was excellent) with friendly service.  Plus, one of the few places in Chicago that makes a whiskey sour the right way -- with egg whites!!!

We met friends here for drinks and ended up staying for dinner.  The bar area was nice, the staff friendly, drink selection was extensive and there was plenty of comfortable seating.  When we moved to the dining area the service got even better.  The staff was pleasant, funny, attentive and informative.  We ordered a wide variety of items from the menu, being that there were 7 of us, and everyone said their meal was excellent.  My steak was perfectly done, just the right size to not slow me down the rest of the night out exploring the city and the prices were fair.  I would definitely recommend giving the Atwood a try if you're in the mood for a nice evening out at a great restaurant.

I'm not a big garbanzo bean fan, but these were GREAT.  I did order the sorbet. I had just read that this place has best ice cream in the Loop. They also offered pumpkin spice ice cream. (I hate pumpkin spice and wish the obsession would die NOW.) Anyway, the mango sorbet was good, presentation was GREAT.  Staff is great. Service was terrific. Although most of the low-star reviews are overly captious and people review Atwood as if the restaurant advertises itself as a five-star restaurant (e.g. the fruit fly in the glass, showing up the Saturday before Christmas w/ no reservation, the lady with a special gluten-free diet), it isn’t bad. At all.  In my opinion, the bartenders are the best part of Atwood. Full of conversation, interesting stories, etc. The cocktails are great. The food - a little overpriced, but I’m not complaining, it’s good food! Price is typical for downtown Chicago, especially being a block from Millenium Park.  I’ve been coming here for years and ever since Pineapple acquired Atwood all has seemed to go down hill. Atwood used to be full of smiles (employees and customers) and the food was really fantastic...Pricey, but fantastic. Ever since Pineapple acquired this property from Kimpton, the management (not staff) have not up to par. They are no where near what they used to be. The managers of Atwood now have a high turnover (I see this because im a somewhat regular), they are condescending to the staff, and don’t really seem to care about the customer - the most important part! It makes me not want to return. Wishing Kimpton would reacquire.

I've been to this restaurant twice. Beautiful mix of modern decor with classy Christmas greens in evidence. Service was prompt and excellent. We shared the smoked trout dip with seasoned crackers. The dip was tangy and tasty and delightfully sprinkled with tiny chive slices. The crackers  were crispy yet a little too salty. The crab cake sandwich was large and delicious, although I didn't realize it would be breaded and fried. The avocado serving was plentiful. The brioche roll was tasty and rich. Greens served with a side of golden mustard salad dressing were crisp and fresh. We shared the chocolate cake for dessert. It was moist and the icing rich and decadent, but I don't see the point of the enormous slice and it cost $14. Overall, a pleasant experience with decent food and great service.
Service and food was really good

HAVE A RESERVATION - EVEN FOR LUNCH. I acknowledge we showed up at 12:30 on a Saturday, before Christmas with no reservation. Still, the hostess said it would be 15 minutes, so we waited...and waited. When I politely inquired after 45 minutes, I was told it would be another half hour. The two-top next to where we we're sitting was empty the whole time and there were several empty tables. I realize they need to accommodate their reservations, but they should have been more forthcoming about the wait or be more organized about the seating. Fortunately, there's a nice Mediterranean place right next door.

It was nothing spectacular. I ordered the endive salad and strip loin for my meal. The salad was fine (although under dressed). My strip loin was supposed to be medium rare, but showed up much closer to medium well/well done. It was nearly inedible and the rest of the dish was nothing special, lightly dressed white beans with plan arugula sprinkled on top.  After dinner the server offered dessert menus, but again had no idea which desserts could be made gluten free. He again had to check with the kitchen. I ordered the panna cotta, which was actually absolute heaven. It is the only reason I've given this restaurant 2 stars. Maybe just go here for dessert?  During our trip this was the second most expensive place we dined (after Roister and only because we got wine there). It definitely was not worth the overall expense.
Nice Steak and American style restaurant around the busy Chicago shopping area. Few blocks behind the main line, yet close to Target, Movie AMC and other shopping retails. Doesnt have good view.
Stylish place with really good food.  A bit pricey though

We arrived excited for breakfast. We were greeted by a hostess that barely would make eye contact and certainly would not smile. When we asked for a table we were instead greeted with an eye roll. Our waiter then came to the table and took our order for breakfast. Again not a smile or sense of welcome to b found. One in our party was explicit about a gluten allergy and went through the menu with the waiter. When breakfast was finally brought to the table the potatoes where found to not be gluten free after a bite of them had already been consumed. He was very flippant about the mistake and joked that "I hope ur not celiac". Lucky for the restaurant that wasn't the case. I was shocked to see the check come without the meal served to the allergic party removed and comped or even discounted. I asked to speak to the manager who was apparently too busy with the 6 patrons total in the restaurant to come over. The waiter did remove the meal after my request and pointing out why it should be. The manager should consider taking the time e to come and interact with his customers. He may find that he has created an unfriendly and uninviting environment with a smile free culture. I wouldn't return even though my meal was good.

The only reason to go to Atwood is the interior/decor. It's beautiful! That being said, I sat at the bar which I love do. The bartender was efficient but unfriendly (I prefer a combo). Once the food arrived, I realized why he might be standoffish; he has to ask every gust "how is everything". The food is ok at best. The meatballs were dry, the kale salad boring and the Brussels sprouts should've been much better (pork was involved). Go in and have drink with a friend, you'll need to being your own conversation, then go to dinner somewhere better.

Everything ordered was delicious. Menu could be more descriptive regarding sides (for example, at breakfast) and how the food is presented though. Friendly staff. Great place to people watch and enjoy a cocktail.

The food was excellent. The service was very good (though the waiter needs to practice pouring wine from a bottle without dripping). The manager was an ass, and wound up costing his service staff some tips from some people in my party because of the attitude he gave us when we asked for three items to be split off the main bill. The kind of person who argues with customers for ten minutes to save about a minute of work should probably find a new line of work.
Food was great and service was great.  Staff thoroughly explained the meal and was friendly.  Ate hear for my boyfriend's birthday.
I don't know when those other pictures were taken of the food but they didn't hold up to what I got. The staff was great and the food came out fast.

Visited Atwood for breakfast. The food was lousy. The hash browns were cold and tasteless. The English muffin was cold and hard. The waiter was slow and clumsy but the bus boys were really good so it made up for that lack of service from the waiter. For $58 l felt ripped off.
Good drinks, kind of generic food but good for a business lunch or pre-theater dinner
Excellent place and service
A place we always stop at when downtown.  Very modern.  Food is always outstanding.
Fine food 🍲
Good place for shopping or business lunch
Great cocktails, friendly staff and beautiful space.
Never disappointing.
The ambient and service were absolutely excellent. Will come back with friends again. A nice place to date or catch up.
Great food promptly prepared by pleasant people.  For $78 spent for one meal I shouldn't leave hungry, which I did. Portions were scant.
Great brunch in a beautiful space in the Loop. It is a bit pricier but the quality is worth it.

Atwood Kitchen located in the Burnham Hotel is a place to go when you feel like taking a refreshing break from the hustle of the city! Enjoy great cocktails or even a light meal! Or take the night time dining experience and find one of the hidden in plain sight gems of Chicago
I appetizers were somewhat small
Late night snacks are awful
Always classic, always delicious.
Amazing place and tasty food ... Definitely will come again! Thank you for the kind service

JJ was our server for my birthday dinner last night. Upon arrival there was a Birthday card signed by many staff of the restaurant. Wow, that was so nice. JJ's service style suited us and he really was professional and courteous as we ordered tapas style. The food was amazing! We enjoyed lamb meatballs, bacon sliders, Brussels sprouts, scallops, deviled eggs, duck fat fried chicken thighs, and a bunch more. Everything was hot and the presentation was beautiful. Thank you JJ and the Atwood for making our dinning experience so enjoyable and thank you for your professional hospitality.
Not a bad spot for some soup! Yum!
Very modern decor and tasty food.

Clean, white, and modern is the best way to describe the interior. Fantastic drink menu with lots of cocktails to choose from and a great menu with lots of well crafted dishes.  Located at street level inside the Hotel Burnham.  Highly recommended for a date night or lunch meeting.

I've been dining at the Atwood since it opened and have experienced the many changes it has gone through.  I believe change can be the mark of an enterprising, imaginative and venturesome dining venture.  The Atwood is where I take out of town guests and important people (twice this week in fact) and everyone I have taken there has raved about the cuisine, the service and the relaxing environment.  I love the latest venture into creative menu selections and just the right amount of food for lunch and for dinner.  I love there being nothing on the menu that is routine or extraneous and much that is surprising. I love the emphasis on healthy and fresh ingredients.  I love the prices.  It's what one would expect of a top-level dining experience but not outrageous, which is what takes place at some top-level dining locations.  The service is always gracious, never rushed and there is always a convivial tone to the room.  Finally, the Burnham Hotel has its own unique ambience and sense of both history and comfort, and love bringing friends to dine there.

Great experience with the staff, decor and the food!  My wife and I had the Lamb meatballs and Peach Caprese, the meatballs were good but he Caprese was wonderful.  For dinner we had the Seared Alaskan Scallops and the Sockeye Salmon.  I finished my salmon almost too quickly, it was grilled and prepared beautifully.  My wife shared her scallops and while they aren't my favorite seafood, they were delicious!  A very warm and inviting experience at the Atwood, we'll be back!
Excellent dinner. Great for a romantic evening! Not too pricey for city dining.
Great brunch, pay a few extra bucks for some awesome chilaquiles!!
Their food is very tasty and the menus does change often which is nice, I would say that it's a bit pricey for the portions but all in all a great restaurant. Highly recommended!

I am giving Atwood a two star rating only because I did like the food. I ordered the chop salad and found it to be very tasty. Unfortunately, the portion was petite at best. For a $17 salad at lunch, you would expect that it would at least have enough greens on it to satisfy the title of "Entree". However, the salad was more of an appetizer. The service was also unsatisfactory. Our server was rude and had the audacity to charge us for a birthday cake item he served us, which we did not even request. I mean we had mentioned it was our friends birthday but there was no further discussion about it. The lunch was over $100 for two salads, a sandwich, a couple beers and a desert item we didn't even order. I can safely say that I will not be coming back, nor will I suggest this disappointment of a "restaurant" to any of my peers.

No one else has reviewed since the renovation.  While I realize I am not in their "crosshairs", I detest the new look - it doesn't match the art deco reliance building at all.  The food was mediocre at best.  The color is stark, sleek, and angular.  The old look was turn of the century (1900 that is) living room comfortable.  And expensive!  Only one of us had a dinner plate, wine and dessert, and the bill was over $100.  Excessive, in my opinion.  I was disappointed.

The food is scrumptious and full of great combinations, all is great so do not hesitate if there are plates that sounds like odd combinations. I recommend the moonlight fish and the salad. The price can be a little high and the portions are on the small side but the flavor is great. Service was good and so were the drinks.

I've easily passed Atwood hundred of times and never once thought to stop in, but I'm so glad I finally did this weekend! The restaurant is in a corner nook of a hotel that has impeccable style and grace. Their menu is top notch and you really can't go wrong with anything.
This is a small but fancy restaurant with a cute corner bar. Old style cocktails and a full selection of liquor. Very nice spot.

Atwood Cafe offers a unique selection for dinner.  I ordered rabbit and my girlfriend ordered char (a type of fish).  I've never seen these on a menu before.  A very good bread was served as an appetizer with a unique spread.  All this was great, but the price was very high ($26 for rabbit).  We even picked the cheaper options.  The portion sizes were very small, especially for the price.  I should get so much food for $26 that I have enough for a leftovers meal the next day, but instead I got half of what I consider a meal and was still hungry.  I used a buy one entree get one free coupon for our meals and I still felt like we paid too much.  I would not go back, although I'm glad I had a chance to try rabbit and char.

This is one of my absolute favorite restaurants in Chicago. When family and friends from out of town visit, it's a convenient place in the center of all the Loop action. The atmosphere is eclectic, like a crazy aunt's library / dining room. But the vibe is so much fun from the great servers to the seasonal menu with comfort foods changed up with unique ingredients that you'd never think could work (but always do). Even the plates and silverware are funky and chic. One of the best, most consistently creative chefs in Chicago!
Casual atmosphere, great food, great service.
Three words: duck bacon rueben.
Near the theatre district and is a great place to go after the show.  We had a 3 course special meal that was for theatre patrons.  Food was great and it is a good deal for the area.

My husband and I had a fantastic experience at the Atwood Cafe. Our server Jillian was not only knowledgeable but personable, I would definitely request her if we go back! Her wine and spirit knowledge was amazing and spot on! Everything else was great too, from the decor to the food, but the service was what set it apart. Will be back to Atwood Cafe!!

My boyfriend and I ate here at the end of the summer...he was about to go away for a few weeks for work and we wanted to celebrate by going somewhere nice.  Atwood Cafe was the perfect choice...the atmosphere was elegant but relaxed, and the service was superb.  Our server, Sang, was excellent.  He was attentive and knowledgeable about everything on the menu, and even hooked us up with a taste of one of the appetizers and a sample of dessert wine because he knew it was a special occasion.  I follow a mainly vegan diet with occasional exceptions, so while there was a vegetarian option, I decided to splurge and get the scallops because I knew the quality would be great (and I was right).  My boyfriend got the pike, which was also delicious.  We ordered a couple of cocktails and an appetizer of fried brussels sprouts while we were waiting for our entrees...maybe not the healthiest way to get in some cruciferous veggies, but probably one of the tastiest!  Atwood Cafe definitely gets it right when it comes to quality over quantity.  I love a good deal and some leftovers to take home as much as the next person, but sometimes you're looking for an overall dining experience, and that's what you get here.  The portions may be on the small side, but everything is so rich and flavorful that you end up completely satisfied.

For four years now, my wife and I have been going to the Atwood as an anniversary treat. Last week's experience was the best yet. Our server (Beth Morrissey) went well above and beyond to make our date special and unforgettable.

Our dining experience at the Atwood Cafe last Saturday evening was beyond exceptional.  I found the Atwood on OpenTable and I had been looking forward to taking a step back in time for quite a while.  Our server Giovanni was charming, warm, enthusiastic, and knowledgable--he transformed cocktails and an early dinner into a magical evening-length affair!  Giovanni did not simply spew at us descriptions of ingredients and preparations that were obviously spoon fed to everyone during a pre-shift meeting.  Instead, he engaged with us and with the menu offering spot on recommendations throughout our meal.  I did not hesitate for a moment to relinquish all decision making responsibilities to Giovanni, and I am glad I did!!  He also paced our meal beautifully, a rare skill during a busy weekend service.  (Bravo to the whole team for that!)  The manager that evening, Kelly, was also a delight.  Not only did she stop by the table to check on us, but she stayed to chat!  We enjoyed a great conversation that was authentic and unhurried, another rare treat from a restaurant manager in downtown Chicago.  The impeccable service was the perfect pairing for the unbelievably GREAT food.  The new Fall menu is creative, dynamic, and very satisfying.  Favorite moments included the pickled mustard seeds on the pheasant crespella, lamb carpaccio, and curried cauliflower.  Wow.  I can't wait to come back.

We ordered the Japanese Breakfast and the Scallops entrees and they both were quite excellent. We also ordered the Mac n Cheese which at first I was a bit skeptical of after reading what it was made with on the menu but we were quite pleasantly surprised after we started eating it. I won't go into what it was made with but all I got to say is you'll have to try it. It will knock your socks off. The salmon that came with the Japanese Breakfast was a more than sufficient portion for me that we carried it home for leftovers. And the scallops were excellent. Sorry I didn't take any photos but the presentation was quite excellent as well. I guess that's an excuse to go back.
Good food, charming, nice location.

went for brunch and the eggs benedict was inedible. the fancy english muffin was un-cuttable and when we asked for another one, figuring this one was unusual, we were brought an un-toasted, unappealing english muffin and told that's the best they could bring. they should stick with thomas' original and allow the meal to be eaten properly.
great ambiance and food, but a bit pricey.

It was raining this evening when my daughter and I, both vegetarians, were looking for an eatery near our hotel, the Silversmith. Just three blocks away, the Atwood is across from Macys and right next to Nordstroms Rack.  There was only one vegetarian/vegan choice on the menu, a spicy lentil dish, and it was delicious and well presented. The pot au creme was one of the nicer desserts I have had in Chicago as well.  Our server was polite without being cloying, and the atmosphere is fun--kind of a theater set of late nouveau meets early deco. The seating was a little cramped, and because so few restaurants are open for dinner in the Loop, the place was pretty packed. Nevertheless, service was good.  I would recommend it for a pre-theater dinner.  A nice dinner for two was about $100 with cocktails.
a nice spot for a brisk business   lunch.

this is our favorite restaurant. my wife and i meet here on fridays for drinks and appetizers at their tiny bar and celebrate all our special occaisions there. if we are at the theatre, symphony or opera, we make a point of eating there as well as wining and dining any out-of-town friends we want to impress.      the spctacular views of state street from their two-story windows in the beautifully restored reliance building (now the luxurious hotel burnham)fairly exude chicago's rich architectural history.    heather terhune's clever blend of nouvelle cuisine and good old chicago comfort food r
